87":"1487","1475":"1475","1463":"1463","1551":"1551","1519":"1519","1507":"1507","1528":"1528","1506":"1506","Gisburn, Yorkshire, England":"Gisburn, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Westby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Selmer, Alf, Erik, Eyvind, Knut, Mauritz, Orvald, Thor.","English: habitational name from any of various places called Westby, for example in Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Yorkshire, all named with Old Norse <i>vestr</i> ‘west, western’ + <i>bý</i> ‘farmstead, village’.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of twenty or more farmsteads, mainly in southeastern Norway, named in Old Norse as <i>Vestbýr</i>, a compound Old Norse <i>vestr</i> ‘west’ + <i>býr</i> ‘settlement’. Compare 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Wesby","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Westby  ."]},{"name":"Westbay","meanings":["Americanized form of Norwegian or Swedish   Westby  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas William de Westby was born in 1463, in London, England, his father, Sir William Robert Singleton, was -17 and his mother, Lady Helen Westby, was -12. He married Isabel Elizabeth Scott in 1487, in Gisburn, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1493, in Gisburn, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1463–1493":"1463–1493","1500–1536":"1500–1536","1506–1551":"1506–1551","1440–1528":"1440–1528","1489–1519":"1489–1519","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1475–1507":"1475–1507","1440":"1440","1493":"1493","1480":"1480","1536":"1536","1489":"1489","1500":"1500","1487":"1487","1475":"1475","1463":"1463","1551":"1551","1519":"1519","1507":"1507","1528":"1528","1506":"1506","Gisburn, Yorkshire, England":"Gisburn, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"1463–1493":"1463–1493","1500–1536":"1500–1536","